{"cursor":"14867","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"An 'ideal chain' (or 'freely-jointed chain') is the simplest model to describe a\npolymer. It only assumes a polymer as a random walk and neglects any kind of\ninteractions among monomers. Although it is simple, its generality gives us some\ninsights about the physics of polymers.\n\nIn this model, monomers are rigid rods of a fixed length l, and their\norientation is completely independent of the orientations and positions of\nneighbouring monomers, to the extent that two monomers can co-exist at the\nsame place.\n","linknr":233,"url":"Ideal_chain","recorded":1362567818,"links":16,"instances":[],"pdf":[],"categories":["Polymer chemistry","Polymer physics"],"headings":["The model","Generality of the model","Entropic elasticity of an ideal chain","See also","External links","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/0/e/d0ee8c538051be32dbc1e4553d0127a7.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/a/d/cada53866f9d2c7ab0e25c6e4972b943.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/d/b/1dbe1b63be7de9d9547ed9f2822cc96d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Ideal_chain_random_walk.png/200px-Ideal_chain_random_walk.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/9/5/09544089b5bf310b1cdea08ee5318aff.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/a/a/0aa64b4d34c62565dedba0a3cc00ad56.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/d/b/1dbe1b63be7de9d9547ed9f2822cc96d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/a/d/cada53866f9d2c7ab0e25c6e4972b943.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/6/2/f621654fb751bcb77f61de0f9af35542.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/f/8/0f86aea0b27c0a196e5f1fed3bf91ca1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/b/f/1bfee43e865d0e74e40b6c43c70d30c6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/6/1/c614a515756fe5fdb838ebe8a7d86003.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/d/f/0df9c83ad9926b12a69cecfde583f407.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/2/5/2253843b4957d40ff01114ce45bbc95a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/6/a/46ac4838f13c2d1ac231e0c9